      { type: "p", text: "This article explains why a steam game has no wishlists in practice, which responses make the situation worse, and how indie developers rebuild a structure that turns attention into consistent wishlist growth." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Why a steam game has no wishlists in practice" },
      { type: "p", text: "When wishlists stay at zero or near zero, the issue is rarely traffic alone. It is almost always about how players experience the decision to wishlist." },
      { type: "p", text: "Several patterns show up repeatedly." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Players never reach a decision point" },
      { type: "p", text: "Most players who see an indie game do not actively decide not to wishlist it. They simply never decide at all." },
      { type: "p", text: "They scroll. They watch. They nod. Then they move on." },
      { type: "p", text: "The absence of a clear decision moment leads to inaction. Inaction is the default behavior online." },
      { type: "p", text: "Steam wishlist growth only happens when the page and messaging push the player toward a specific choice." },
      { type: "h3", text: "The Steam page explains but does not persuade" },
      { type: "p", text: "Many developers build Steam pages that are accurate and informative." },
      { type: "p", text: "Accurate does not mean persuasive." },
      { type: "p", text: "A page can clearly describe mechanics, features, and inspirations while still giving no reason to act now. When nothing creates urgency or relevance, players postpone the action indefinitely." },
      { type: "p", text: "Postponed actions rarely happen later." },
      { type: "h3", text: "The audience is too broad to convert" },
      { type: "p", text: "When developers are unsure who the game is really for, the page tries to speak to everyone." },
      { type: "p", text: "This creates vague positioning." },
      { type: "p", text: "Players struggle to recognize themselves in the experience. If they cannot quickly say this game is for me, they do not wishlist." },
      { type: "p", text: "Steam wishlist growth depends on sharp relevance, not broad appeal." },
      { type: "h3", text: "External traffic arrives with mismatched expectations" },
      { type: "p", text: "Traffic sources matter more than volume." },
      { type: "p", text: "A player arriving from a short video, a Reddit post, or a streamer has a different mindset. Sending all of them to the same generic presentation creates friction." },
      { type: "p", text: "When expectations are not met quickly, players disengage before reaching the wishlist button." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Developers confuse feedback with intent" },
      { type: "p", text: "Nice comments feel encouraging." },
      { type: "p", text: "Looks interesting Cool concept Wish you luck" },
      { type: "p", text: "These are social signals, not buying signals. Many players express support without any intention to wishlist or buy." },
      { type: "p", text: "Steam wishlist growth is driven by behavior, not sentiment." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Common reactions that keep wishlists at zero" },
      { type: "p", text: "When developers notice that their steam game has no wishlists, they often respond in ways that feel productive but miss the root cause." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Posting more content everywhere" },
      { type: "p", text: "Increasing posting frequency feels like action." },
      { type: "p", text: "If conversion is broken, more traffic simply increases the number of people who do not wishlist. This creates emotional fatigue without fixing the system." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Adding more detail to the Steam page" },
      { type: "p", text: "Developers often assume players need more information." },
      { type: "p", text: "They add longer descriptions, more screenshots, more explanations, and more systems." },
      { type: "p", text: "This increases cognitive load. Players hesitate instead of committing." },
      { type: "p", text: "Steam wishlist growth improves when clarity increases, not when complexity does." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Waiting for the algorithm to help" },
      { type: "p", text: "Steam algorithms reward engagement signals. They do not rescue weak pages." },
      { type: "p", text: "If direct visitors do not wishlist, algorithmic exposure would likely perform the same or worse." },
      { type: "p", text: "Fixing conversion always comes before scaling visibility." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Copying successful games surface tactics" },
      { type: "p", text: "It is tempting to copy the layout, wording, or trailer style of successful titles." },
      { type: "p", text: "Without understanding why those choices work for that specific audience, copying creates mismatches." },
      { type: "p", text: "Systems transfer poorly. Principles transfer well." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Assuming wishlists will come later" },
      { type: "p", text: "Some developers postpone worrying about wishlists until closer to launch." },
      { type: "p", text: "This compounds the problem. Low early wishlist growth reduces long term visibility and momentum." },
      { type: "p", text: "Steam wishlist growth is cumulative. Delays are costly." },
      { type: "h2", text: "The correct system behind steam wishlist growth" },
      { type: "p", text: "When developers stop asking why a steam game has no wishlists and start designing a system, patterns emerge." },
      { type: "p", text: "A reliable system has five connected parts." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Step one define the real wishlist audience" },
      { type: "p", text: "The wishlist audience is not every potential player." },
      { type: "p", text: "It is the subset most likely to care at the current stage of development." },
      { type: "p", text: "This group shares expectations about genre, scope, visuals, and progression. They understand what the game is trying to be." },
      { type: "p", text: "If you cannot describe this group in one sentence, the Steam page will struggle to speak to them." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Step two create a clear reason to wishlist now" },
      { type: "p", text: "Wishlisting is not a neutral action. It requires motivation." },
      { type: "p", text: "Players wishlist to track progress, anticipate a milestone, or wait for a specific moment." },
      { type: "p", text: "Your page must make that reason explicit." },
      { type: "p", text: "Without a clear why now, players default to later. Later rarely arrives." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Step three design the Steam page as a decision funnel" },
      { type: "p", text: "A Steam page is not read top to bottom. It is scanned." },
      { type: "p", text: "The first visual impression, the opening seconds of the trailer, the short description, and the screenshot order work together." },
      { type: "p", text: "Their job is to guide the visitor toward one conclusion." },
      { type: "p", text: "This is worth wishlisting." },
      { type: "p", text: "Steam wishlist growth often improves significantly after aligning these elements, even without new traffic." },
      { type: "h3", text: "Step four align traffic sources with page framing" },
      { type: "p", text: "Every traffic source creates expectations." },
